{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}) be any function. Prove that the graph {\i \u915?}{\sub {\i f}} of {\i f} is isomorphic to {\i A}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using the elements from the previous exercise, we know that {\i f\u770?} is injective from {\i A} into {\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}. This property is inherited to any restriction of the codomain {\i Z}\u8196?\u8838?\u8196?{\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}, and corresponding implied restriction of the domain to {\i Y}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f\u770?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}({\i Z})\u8196?\u8838?\u8196?{\i A}. In particular, here, {\i Y}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i A} and {\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u915?}{\sub {\i f}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f\u770?}({\i A}). We now consider $\\overline\{f\} \\in (A \\to \\Gamma_f), \\overline\{f\} = (a \\mapsto \\hat\{f\}(a))$. We can see that $\\overline\{f\}$ is injective from being a restriction of an injective function to a smaller codomain. We also know that $\\overline\{f\}$ is surjective, since its domain is its image. Therefore, $\\overline\{f\}$ is a bijection. This means that {\i A}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i \u915?}{\sub {\i f}}.\par}
