{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Describe as explicitly as you can all terms in the canonical decomposition of the function {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?(\u8477?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u8450?) defined by {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i r}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i e}{\super 2{\i \u960?}{\i i}{\i r}}). (This exercise matches one assigned previously, which one?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Firstly, elements of \u8477? are equivalent by this map (they have the same output) if they vary by 1 from each other. This is a reference to the equivalence relation \u8764? in exercise 1.6. Therefore, we will use \u8477?/\u8764?\u8197?\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i S}{\super 1} in our decomposition. Obviously, the map from (\u8477?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u8477?/\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?), which maps each element of \u8477? to respective their equivalence class is a surjection (since there\u8217's no empty equivalence class).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Secondly, as mentioned, we have a bijection {\i f\u771?} between \u8477?/\u8764? and {\i S}{\super 1}, the circle group of unit complex numbers, namely {\i f\u771?}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i e}{\super 2{\i \u960?}{\i i}{\i x}}, where each element {\i x} of \u8477?/\u8764? can be understood to correspond to a (class representative) value in the interval [0,\u8198?1[.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Finally, we do the canonical injection of {\i S}{\super 1} into its superset \u8450?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.9)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Show that if {\i A}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}\u8242? and {\i B}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i B}\u8242? , and further {\i A}\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709? and {\i A}\u8242?\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i B}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?, then {\i A}\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}\u8242?\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}\u8242?. Conclude that the operation {\i A}\u8720?{\i B} (as described in \u167?1.4) is well-defined up to isomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We suppose the aforementioned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i f}{\sub {\i A}} be a bijection from {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8242?, and {\i f}{\sub {\i B}} be a bijection from {\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8242?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We define the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$f \\in (A \\cup B \\to A' \\cup B'),
\\text\{ such that \}
\\begin\{cases\}
    \\forall a \\in A, \\; f(a) = f_A(a) \\\\
    \\forall b \\in B, \\; f(b) = f_B(b)
\\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This function is a well-defined function, since {\i A}\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?: every element of the domain has one, and only one, possible image.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, we define:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$g \\in (A' \\cup B' \\to A \\cup B),
\\text\{ such that \}
\\begin\{cases\}
    \\forall a \\in A', \\; g(a) = f_A^\{-1\}(a) \\\\
    \\forall b \\in B', \\; g(b) = f_B^\{-1\}(b)
\\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, because {\i A}\u8242?\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i B}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?, {\i g} is well-defined.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us study {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}. We have: $$\\begin\{cases\}
    \\forall a \\in A, \\; g(f(a)) = f_A^\{-1\}(f_A(a)) = a \\\\
    \\forall b \\in B, \\; g(f(b)) = f_B^\{-1\}(f_B(b)) = b
\\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hence, {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}}. Similarly, {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}\u8242?\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}\u8242?}. Therefore, {\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}, {\i f} is a bijection, and {\i A}\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}\u8242?\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}\u8242?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We\u8217'll now do a shift in notation. Let be some arbitrary sets {\i A} and {\i B}. Let be {\i A}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i A}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i B}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i B}{\sub 2} such that {\i A}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1\}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i A}, {\i A}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{2\}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i A}, {\i B}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1\}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}, and {\i B}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{2\}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}. This means {\i A}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}{\sub 1}, {\i A}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}{\sub 2}, {\i B}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i B}{\sub 1}, and {\i B}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i B}{\sub 2}. It also means {\i A}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i A}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709? and {\i B}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?{\i B}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?. From the above, this implies {\i A}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i A}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i B}{\sub 2}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that the disjoint union of {\i A} and {\i B} is indeed well-defined, up to isomorphism: so long as 2 respective copies of {\i A} and {\i B} are made in a way that their intersection is empty, the 2 respective unions of 1 copy each will be isomorphic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.10)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Show that if {\i A} and {\i B} are finite sets, then |{\i B}{\super {\i A}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i B}|{\super |{\i A}|}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The number of |{\i B}{\super {\i A}}| functions in {\i B}{\super {\i A}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}) can be counted in the following way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For each element {\i a} of {\i A}, of which there are |{\i A}|, we can pick any element of {\i B} as the image; a total of |{\i B}| choices per choice of {\i a}. This means |{\i B}|\u8197?\u215?\u8197?...\u8197?\u215?\u8197?|{\i B}|, a total of |{\i A}| times. Hence, |{\i B}{\super {\i A}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i B}|{\super |{\i A}|}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.11)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In view of Exercise 2.10, it is not unreasonable to use 2{\super {\i A}} to denote the set of functions from an arbitrary set {\i A} to a set with 2 elements (say \u55349?\u56633?\u8196?=\u8196?\{0,\u8198?1\}). Prove that there is a bijection between 2{\super {\i A}} and the power set \u55349?\u56491?({\i A}) of {\i A}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Simply put, every subset {\i A}{\sub {\i i}} of {\i A} is built through a series of |{\i A}| choices: for each element {\i a} in {\i A}, do we keep the element {\i a} in our subset {\i A}{\sub {\i i}} (output 1) or do we remove it (output 0) ? It is then easy to see that such a series of choices can easily be encoded as a unique function in {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u55349?\u56633?. The totality of such series of choices thus corresponds both to the space {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u55349?\u56633?, and to the powerset \u55349?\u56491?({\i A}), and there is a bijection between the two.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Section 3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let \u55349?\u56478? be a category. Consider a structure \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} with:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}})\u8196?\u8788?\u8196?{\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab for {\i A}, {\i B} objects of \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} (hence, objects of \u55349?\u56478?), {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B})\u8196?\u8788?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i A})\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Show how to make this into a category.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 3.1.a) Composition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, to make things clearer and more rigorous, let us distinguish composition in \u55349?\u56478? as \u8728? and composition in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} as \u8902?. We define \u8902? as: $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    & \\forall f \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (B, A) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, B), \\\\
    & \\forall g \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (C, B) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (B, C), \\\\
    & \\exists h \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (C, A) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, C), \\\\
    & f \\star g \\coloneqq g \\circ f = h
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will now show that \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} with \u8902? verifies the other axioms of a category (namely identity and associativity of composition).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 3.1.b) Identity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since \u55349?\u56478? is a category, since \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} has the same objects, and since, by definition, for all object {\i A}, we have {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}}({\i A},\u8198?{\i A})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i A}), we can take every {\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i A}) as the same identity in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}. We can verify that this is compatible with \u8902?:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    \\forall A, B & \\in Obj (\\mathcal\{C\})        &=& \\;  Obj (\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\})        , \\\\
    \\exists id_A & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, A) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (A, A) , \\\\
    \\exists id_B & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (B, B) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (B, B) , \\\\
    \\forall f    & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, B) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (B, A) , \\\\
    f            & =   f    \\circ id_A          &=& \\;  id_A \\star f                  , \\\\
    f            & =   id_B \\circ    f          &=& \\;  f    \\star id_B                 \\\\
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 3.1.c) Associativity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using associativity in \u55349?\u56478?, we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    \\forall A, B, C, D & \\in Obj (\\mathcal\{C\})        &=& \\;  Obj (\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\})        , \\\\
    \\forall f          & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, B) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (B, A) , \\\\
    \\forall g          & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (B, C) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (C, B) , \\\\
    \\forall h          & \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (C, D) &=& \\;  Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (D, C) , \\\\
\\end\{aligned\}$$ $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    h \\star (g \\star f) &=&  h \\star (f  \\circ g) \\\\
                        &=& (f \\circ  g) \\circ h  \\\\
                        &=&  f \\circ (g  \\circ h) \\\\
                        &=& (g \\circ  h) \\star f  \\\\
                        &=& (h \\star  g) \\star f  \\\\
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, \u8902? is associative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We conclude that \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} is a category.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If {\i A} is a finite set, how large is {\i E}{\i n}{\i d}{\sub Set}({\i A}) ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We know that, in Set, {\i E}{\i n}{\i d}{\sub Set}({\i A})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i A}{\super {\i A}}. From a previous exercise, we know that |{\i B}{\super {\i A}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i B}|{\super |{\i A}|}, therefore |{\i E}{\i n}{\i d}{\sub Set}({\i A})|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i A}|{\super |{\i A}|}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Formulate precisely what it means to say that "1{\sub {\i a}} is an identity with respect to composition" in Example 3.3, and prove this assertion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Example 3.3 is that of a category over a set {\i S} with a (reflexive, transitive) relation \u8764?, where the objects of the category are the elements of {\i S}, and the homset between two elements {\i a} and {\i b} is the singleton ({\i a},\u8198?{\i b}) if {\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}, and \u8709? otherwise. Composition \u8728? is given by transitivity of \u8764?, where ({\i b},\u8198?{\i c})\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i a},\u8198?{\i c}). Reflexivity gives the identities ({\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i a}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i a},\u8198?{\i a}) for any element {\i a}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this context, to say that "1{\sub {\i a}} is an identity with respect to composition" means that we can cancel out an element of the form ({\i a},\u8198?{\i a}) from a composition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Formally, we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S},\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?{\i b})\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?({\i a},\u8198?{\i a})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 proving that ({\i b},\u8198?{\i b}) is indeed a post-identity, and ({\i a},\u8198?{\i a}) a pre-identity, in this context.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Can we define a category in the style of Example 3.3, using the relation < on the set \u8484? ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Description of example 3.3 in the exercise 3.3 just above.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Naively, saying like in example 3.3 "there is a singleton homset Hom({\i a},\u8198?{\i b}) each time we have {\i a}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i b}", we cannot define such a category, since < is not reflexive, and we would thus lack identity morphisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, in a roundabout way, we can define a category over the {\i negation} of <: "there is a singleton homset Hom({\i a},\u8198?{\i b}) each time we DO NOT have {\i a}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i b}". Namely this corresponds to the relation \u8805?, which is, itself, reflexive, transitive (and antisymmetric), and is a valid instance of the kind of category presented in example 3.3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In fact, the pair (\u8484?,\u8198?\u8196?\u8805?\u8196?) is an instance of what is called a "totally ordered set", which is a more restrictive kind of "partially ordered set" (also called "poset" for short). Consequently, this kind of category is called a "poset category".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Explain in what sense Example 3.4 is an instance of the categories considered in Example 3.3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Description of example 3.3 in the exercise 3.3 just above.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Example 3.4 describes a category {\i S\u770?} where the objects are the subsets of a set {\i S} (equivalently: elements of the powerset \u55349?\u56491?({\i S}) of {\i S}), and morphisms between two subsets {\i A} and {\i B} of {\i S} are singleton (or empty) homsets based on whether the inclusion is true (or false).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inclusion of sets, \u8834?, is also an order relation, this time between the elements of a set of sets (here, \u55349?\u56491?({\i S})). This means inclusion is reflexive, transitive, and antisymmetric. This makes {\i S\u770?} a poset category, and thus another instance of example 3.3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Define a category {\i V} by taking {\i O}{\i b}{\i j}({\i V})\u8196?=\u8196?\u8469?, and {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub {\i V}}({\i n},\u8198?{\i m})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i M}{\i a}{\i t}{\sub \u8477?}({\i m},\u8198?{\i n}), the set of {\i m}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i n} matrices with real entries, for all {\i n},\u8198?{\i m}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469?. (I will leave the reader the task to make sense of a matrix with 0 rows or columns.) Use product of matrices to define composition. Does this category \u8217'feel\u8217' familiar ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The formulation of the exercise is strange. It says to use the product of matrices to define composition, and to have homsets be sets of matrices, but objects of the category are supposed to be integers. I don\u8217't know of any matrix with real entries that maps an integer to an integer in this way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We thus infer that the meaning of the exercise can be one of two things.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Either we suppose the set of objects could rather be understood as "something isomorphic to \u8469?", ie, the collection of real vector spaces with finite bases (ie, \u8704?{\i n}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469?,\u8198?\u8477?{\super {\i n}}). In which case, this is just the category of real vector spaces with finite basis (and linear maps as morphisms), which is a subcategory of the category real vector spaces (commonly called {\i V}{\i e}{\i c}{\i t}{\sub \u8477?}). In this context, any morphism starting from 0\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?\u8477?{\super 0}\u8196?=\u8196?\{0\} is just the injection of the origin into the codomain; and any morphism ending at 0 is the mapping of all elements to the origin.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Otherwise, we understand this as "yes, the objects of the category are integers: this means you should ignore the actual content of the matrices, and instead consider only their effect on the dimensionality of domains and codomains". In this case, this category is a complete directed graph over \u8469? where each edge corresponds to the change in dimension (from domain to codomain) caused by a given linear map.\par}
