{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Define carefully objects and morphisms in Example 3.7, and draw the diagram corresponding to composition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Example 3.7 (on coslice categories) refers to example 3.5 (on slice categories). Let\u8217's go over slice categories (since example 3.5 asks the reader to "check all [their various properties]").\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 3.7.1) Slice categories\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Slice categories are categories made by singling out an object (say {\i A}) in some parent (larger) category (say \u55349?\u56478?), and studying all morphisms into that object. These morphisms become the objects of a new category (ie, for any {\i Z} of \u55349?\u56478?, {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) is an object of the slice category, called \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} in this context). In the slice category, morphisms are defined as those morphism in \u55349?\u56478? that preserve composition between 2 morphisms into {\i A}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note that there exist pairs of morphisms {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) and {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) between which there is no morphism that exists in the slice category. One such example we can make is in ({\i V}{\i e}{\i c}{\i t}{\sub \u8477?}){\sub \u8477?{\super 2}} (see notes "On the morphisms of slice and coslice categories" for more details).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.1.a) Identity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A generic identity morphism is expressed diagrammatically in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that since {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i Z}} in \u55349?\u56478?, this is compatible with the definition of a (pre-/right-)unit morphism in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}}. Also, since the only maps post-{\i f} are maps from {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}, we have {\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}} as the (post-/left-)unit for every morphism {\i f} (ie, {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.1.b) Composition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Taking 3 objects of the slice category ({\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}), {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) and {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A})), and two morphisms ({\i \u963?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 2} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u963?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}), and {\i \u964?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 2} to {\i f}{\sub 3} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u964?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 3})), we have that {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u963?} and {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub 3}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u964?}. This is expressed as the following commutative diagram.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Composition of morphisms is then defined as {\i \u964?}{\sub {\i A}}\u8728?{\sub {\i A}}{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i A}} as a mapping from {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 3}, such that {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub 3}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?({\i \u964?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u963?}). This can be understood through the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Which commutes, because we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    f_1 &=&  f_2              \\circ \\sigma  \\\\
        &=& (f_3 \\circ  \\tau) \\circ \\sigma  \\\\
        &=&  f_3 \\circ (\\tau  \\circ \\sigma)
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Thus, we have a working composition of morphisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.1.c) Associativity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We take 4 objects of the slice category ({\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}), {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}), {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) and {\i f}{\sub 4}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 4}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A})), and three morphisms ({\i \u963?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 2}, {\i \u964?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 2} to {\i f}{\sub 3}, and {\i \u965?}{\sub {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 3} to {\i f}{\sub 4}). Using composition defined as above, we have\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
f_1 &=& f_4 \\circ ( \\upsilon \\circ (\\tau  \\circ \\sigma)) \\\\
    &=& f_4 \\circ ((\\upsilon \\circ  \\tau) \\circ \\sigma ) \\\\
\\Rightarrow && \\\\
& &  \\upsilon_A \\circ (\\tau_A  \\circ \\sigma_A) \\\\
&=& (\\upsilon_A \\circ  \\tau_A) \\circ \\sigma_A
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Through associativity in \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 3.7.2) Coslice categories\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A coslice category \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i A}} is similar, except it takes the morphisms coming {\i from} a chosen object {\i A}, rather than those going {\i to} this object {\i A}. Below is a commutative diagram in the style of the one of the textbook for slice categories.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can similarly show that this also defines a category.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.2.a) Identity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A generic identity morphism is expressed diagrammatically in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i A}} as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that since {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i Z}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} in \u55349?\u56478?, this is compatible with the definition of a (post-/left-)unit morphism in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i A}}. Also, since the only maps pre-{\i f} are maps from {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}, we have {\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}} as the (pre-/right-)unit for every morphism {\i f} (ie, {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.2.b) Composition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Taking 3 objects of the slice category ({\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1}), {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}) and {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 3})), and two morphisms ({\i \u963?}{\super {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 2} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u963?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}), and {\i \u964?}{\super {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 2} to {\i f}{\sub 3} via a \u55349?\u56478?-morphism {\i \u964?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 3})), we have that {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 2} and {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u964?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 3}. This is expressed as the following commutative diagram.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Composition of morphisms is then defined as {\i \u964?}{\super {\i A}}\u8728?{\super {\i A}}{\i \u963?}{\super {\i A}} as a mapping from {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 3}, such that {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i \u964?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u963?})\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1}. This can be understood through the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Which commutes, because we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    f_3 &=&  \\tau \\circ                f_2  \\\\
        &=&  \\tau \\circ (\\sigma  \\circ f_1) \\\\
        &=& (\\tau \\circ  \\sigma) \\circ f_1
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Thus, we have a working composition of morphisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.7.2.c) Associativity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We take 4 objects of the slice category ({\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1}), {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}), {\i f}{\sub 3}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 3}) and {\i f}{\sub 4}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 4})), and three morphisms ({\i \u963?}{\super {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 1} to {\i f}{\sub 2}, {\i \u964?}{\super {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 2} to {\i f}{\sub 3}, and {\i \u965?}{\super {\i A}} mapping {\i f}{\sub 3} to {\i f}{\sub 4}). Using composition defined as above, we have\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
f_4 &=& ( \\upsilon \\circ (\\tau  \\circ \\sigma)) \\circ f_1 \\\\
    &=& ((\\upsilon \\circ  \\tau) \\circ \\sigma ) \\circ f_1 \\\\
\\Rightarrow && \\\\
    & &  \\upsilon^A \\circ (\\tau^A  \\circ \\sigma^A) \\\\
    &=& (\\upsilon^A \\circ  \\tau^A) \\circ \\sigma^A
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Through associativity in \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.8)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A subcategory \u55349?\u56478?\u8242? of a category \u55349?\u56478? consists of a collection of objects of \u55349?\u56478?, with morphisms {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?\u8242?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B})\u8196?\u8838?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) for all objects {\i A}, {\i B} in {\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?\u8242?), such that identities and compositions in \u55349?\u56478? make \u55349?\u56478?\u8242? into a category. A subcategory \u55349?\u56478?\u8242? is {\i full} if {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?\u8242?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) for all {\i A}, {\i B} in {\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?\u8242?). Construct a category of {\i infinite sets} and explain how it may be viewed as a full subcategory of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To put it less technically, a "subcategory" \u55349?\u56478?\u8242? is just "picking only certain items of a base category \u55349?\u56478?, and making sure that things stay closed uneder morphism composition". It is "full" if {\i all} morphisms between the objects that remain are also conserved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can construct a category {\b I}{\b n}{\b f}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} of infinite sets by taking all the objects {\i A} of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} such that \u8708?{\i n}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469?,\u8198?|{\i A}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n}, and only homsets between these objects. This is clearly a subcategory of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, since it inherits all identity morphisms, composition works the same, and so does associativity; also, restricting the choice of homsets makes it so that the category is closed (you can\u8217't reach a finite set via a homset that went from an infinite to a finite set).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For this category to not be full, there would need to be some homset that loses a morphism, or fully disappears, in the ordeal. However, there is no restriction as to the kind of morphism that is conserved, so any homset that is kept is identical to its original version. Finally, homsets between infinite sets are also infinite sets, so they don\u8217't disappear in this operation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Consequently {\b I}{\b n}{\b f}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} defined as such is a full subcategory of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.9)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An alternative to the notion of multiset introduced in \u167?2.2 is obtained by considering sets endowed with equivalence relations; equivalent elements are taken to be multiple instances of elements \u8217'of the same kind\u8217'. Define a notion of morphism between such enhanced sets, obtaining a category {\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} containing (a \u8217'copy\u8217' of) {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} as a full subcategory. (There may be more than one reasonable way to do this! This is intentionally an open-ended exercise.) Which objects in {\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} determine ordinary multisets as defined in \u167?2.2, and how? Spell out what a morphism of multisets would be from this point of view. (There are several natural notions of morphisms of multisets. Try to define morphisms in MSet so that the notion you obtain for ordinary multisets captures your intuitive understanding of these objects.) [\u167?2.2, \u167?3.2, 4.5]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us recall how multisets were defined in \u167?2.2. Since duplicate elements do not exist in sets, multisets were instead defined as functions from a set {\i S} to \u8469?*, the set of (nonzero) positive integers. This allows each element in {\i S} to have a "count", thereby encoding the intuitive notion of multiset. A similar, and equivalent (isomorphic), way of defining it is {\i via} pairs ({\i s},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8469?*, which is simpler to think about. We\u8217'll call this category {\b C}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, for "count multiset" (TODO: probably has a conventional and better name, but I don\u8217't know it). As for morphisms in {\b C}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, we can consider that for any multisets {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8469?* and {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i B}}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8469?*, the homset from {\i A} to {\i B} is simply the set functions from {\i S}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8469?* to {\i S}{\sub {\i B}}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?\u8469?* as usual.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first notice that if we restrict {\b C}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} to only the objects for which all elements have a count of 1, and where morphisms only ever output to \{1\} in the second coordinate (a subcategory we can call {\b C}{\b 1}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, for example), we get a "copy" of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}: {\b C}{\b 1}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} and {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} are isomorphic in {\b C}{\b a}{\b t}. This is a full subcategory because there are no morphisms that map counts to anything else than \{1\} if we restrict our objects to this form; so all morphisms between the kept objects are also kept.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now let us do a similar construction, but based on equivalence classes instead. We know that each equivalence class over a set corresponds uniquely to a partition of that set. By considering only these partitions (these "sets of sets") as objects, we can build a category {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} (for "equivalence multiset"). The "count" corresponds simply to the cardinal of a top-level element in the partition. For example, the top-level elements of {\i M}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i S}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i S}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i S}{\sub 3}\}\u8196?=\u8196?\{\{{\i a}\},\u8198?\{{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\},\u8198?\{{\i d},\u8198?{\i e},\u8198?{\i f}\}\} would be understood to have counts |{\i S}{\sub 1}|\u8196?=\u8196?1, |{\i S}{\sub 2}|\u8196?=\u8196?2 and |{\i S}{\sub 3}|\u8196?=\u8196?3 respectively.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As for morphisms in {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, they simply map each top-level element of the domain multiset (a distinct subset of the original set) to some other top-level elements in the codomain multiset. This has precisely the same effect as mapping pairs of "value and count" as seen in the previous {\b C}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} construction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this example, any set itself, when "injected" (by a functor) into {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} would just nest all of its elements into singletons. I.e., {\i S}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\} in {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} would become {\i S}\u8196?=\u8196?\{\{{\i a}\},\u8198?\{{\i b}\},\u8198?\{{\i c}\}\} in {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t}. This also shows how restricting {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} to "only objects that are a set of (toplevel) singletons" makes {\b E}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} have a "copy" of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} as a full subcategory (for similar arguments as above).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Yet another example could be something akin to polynomials with integer coefficients on freeform indeterminates of degree 1 (which would be our set elements); raising the operators one rank, a product of freeform variables with integer powers (multiplicities), etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 3.10)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the objects of a category \u55349?\u56478? are not (necessarily) sets, it is not clear how to make sense of a notion of \u8217'subobject\u8217' in general. In some situations it does make sense to talk about subobjects, and the subobjects of any given object {\i A} in \u55349?\u56478? are in one-to-one correspondence with the morphisms {\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i \u937?} for a fixed, special object {\i \u937?} of \u55349?\u56478?, called a subobject classifier. Show that {\b S}{\b e}{\b t} has a subobject classifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We define the set \u55349?\u56633?\u8196?=\u8196?\{0,\u8198?1\}, aka the binary alphabet or booleans, as the subobject classifier of {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}. For any subset {\i A} of {\i B}, there is a unique map {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u55349?\u56633?, such that \u8704?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?{\i f}({\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?1\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A} (otherwise {\i f}({\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?0, of course, as the equivalence and lack of alternatives to 0 as an output imply). The map {\i f} always fully describes {\i A} from its relationship with {\i B}.\par}
