{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Composition is defined for {\i two} morphisms. If more than 2 morphisms are given, one may compose them in several ways, so that every step only consists in composing 2 morphisms. Prove that for any such valid sequence of morphisms, the order of parentheses doesn\u8217't matter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This boils down to showing that associativity is a global property, that doesn\u8217't just make parentheses meaningless when there are 3 elements and 2 operators between them, but in general {\i n} elements with ({\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1) operators between them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: A useful way of visualizing this is representing the order of operations as a binary tree, and noticing that applying associativity (forwards or backwards) is just a tree rotation (resp. right or left) at a given node. Then it is easy to show that one can always obtain a "left comb binary tree". Since every choice of parentheses is equal to this left comb choice, and equality is transitive, every choice of parentheses is equal to every other choice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To be more rigorous, we will proceed by induction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hypothesis: {\i P}({\i n}) = "for a given {\i n}, for {\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1} any valid, composable, ordered sequence of morphisms in our base category \u55349?\u56478?, any choice {\i H} of parentheses to compose elements of this sequence 2-by-2, giving a formula {\i s}{\sub {\i H}}, will lead to the same result, which can be seen by always having {\i s}{\sub {\i H}}\u8196?=\u8196?(\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?({\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?){\i f}{\sub 1}".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Initialization: We initialize at {\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?3; the validity is immediate as it is precisely the definition of associativity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Heredity: We suppose the hypothesis {\i P}({\i n}) true for a given {\i n}\u8196?\u8805?\u8196?3; let us show that this implies that the hypothesis is true for {\i P}({\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What this means is that, no matter the composable ordered sequence {\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1} of {\i n} functions, for a fixed {\i n}, the order of parentheses does not matter. Note that though {\i n} is chosen and fixed; the statement is true for EVERY (ordered, composable) sequence of functions. We add a new function {\i g} to this sequence. By a simple renaming of the functions, we deduce that it doesn\u8217't matter where we insert {\i g}, so we\u8217'll insert it at the very right to simplify our argument, giving us the sequence {\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1}{\i g}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here, there are 3 cases. Either:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i g} is part of the last composition (i.e., it\u8217's not in a semantically necessary parenthethical grouping; it can be made external to all parentheses),\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i g} is part of the first composition (i.e., the first operation is ({\i f}{\sub 1}{\i g}))\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab it isn\u8217't either (it\u8217's inside some non-removable parentheses, and needs to be composed earlier on, but not as the first operation).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If {\i g} is part of the last composition, then by applying the hypothesis {\i P}({\i n}) to the terms {\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1}, we immediately find that our new sequence can be made equal to ((\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?({\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?){\i f}{\sub 1}){\i g}, which is precisely what we wanted for {\i P}({\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If {\i g} is part of the first composition, we isolate it so that it isn\u8217't anymore. To do so, we apply "backwards" associativity on the grouping of terms {\i F}{\sub {\i k}}({\i f}{\sub 1}{\i g}) in order to obtain ({\i F}{\sub {\i k}}{\i f}{\sub 1}){\i g}, where {\i F}{\sub {\i k}} is the appropriate choice of ({\i f}{\sub {\i k}}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 2}) such that associativity can be applied (with 2\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i k}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i n}). This makes it so that our problem is identical to our final case, solved just below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If {\i g} is part of neither the first nor last composition, then we consider the innermost composition ({\i f}{\sub {\i k}}{\i f}{\sub {\i k}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}) to be a single element {\i h}. We now have a sequence of only {\i n} terms. We apply our hypothesis {\i P}({\i n}). This makes {\i g} the outermost right term, part of the last composition. Unravelling {\i h} back into two members, we see that we are back at our initial case, with an arbitrary order of parentheses for the {\i f}{\sub {\i n}}{\i f}{\sub {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub 1} terms, and {\i g} outermost. We already saw that this implied {\i P}({\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: since we have initialization and heredity of our hypothesis in all cases, we can conclude by induction that it is true for all {\i n}\u8196?\u8805?\u8196?3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In Example 3.3 we have seen how to construct a category from a set endowed with a relation, provided the latter is reflexive and transitive. For what types of relations is the corresponding category a groupoid (cf. Example 4.6) ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We remind example 4.6 : a groupoid is a category in which every morphism is an isomorphism. This means that every morphism needs to be 2-way invertible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this context, this means that for every morphism {\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}, there should be a corresponding inverse morphism {\i b}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i a}. This property is precisely the symmetry of a relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that all sets with an equivalence relation can be reconstructed into a groupoid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i A}, {\i B} be objects of a category \u55349?\u56478?, and {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) a morphism. Prove that if {\i f} has a pre-inverse, then {\i f} is an epimorphism. Show that the converse does not hold, by giving an explicit example of a category and an epimorphism without a pre-inverse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.3.a)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f} has a pre-inverse \u8658? {\i f} is an epimorphism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let \u55349?\u56478? be a category. Let {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}), having some pre-inverse which we\u8217'll call {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i A}):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z} be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?, and $\\beta', \\beta" \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (B, Z)$:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    \\beta' \\circ f = \\beta'' \\circ f
        & \\Rightarrow (\\beta' \\circ  f) \\circ g  = (\\beta'' \\circ  f) \\circ g  \\\\
        & =            \\beta' \\circ (f  \\circ g) =  \\beta'' \\circ (f  \\circ g) \\\\
        & =            \\beta' \\circ id_B         =  \\beta'' \\circ id_B \\\\
        & =            \\beta'                    =  \\beta''
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that {\i f} is an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.3.b)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f} is an epimorphism $\\;\\not\\!\\!\\!\\Rightarrow$ {\i f} has a pre-inverse\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As was mentioned in the text, "order" categories (poset categories) where there\u8217's only at most one morphism between any two objects makes it so that every morphism is trivially an epimorphism (i.e., since there is at most one morphism "\u8804?" between any two elements, so you always have $\\beta' = \\beta" = \\leq$, and since $\\beta' = \\beta"$ is always true, anything implication with it as a necessary condition is also true, and therefore every morphism is true). However, only identities have any kind of inverse (since they are isomorphisms, they are their own inverse); other combinations of elements go one-way, because of antisymmetry.\par}
