{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that the composition of two monomorphisms is a monomorphism. Deduce that one can define a subcategory \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} of a category \u55349?\u56478? by taking the same objects as in \u55349?\u56478?, and defining {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}}}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) to be the subset of {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) consisting of monomorphisms, for all objects {\i A}, {\i B}. (Cf. Exercise 3.8; of course, in general \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} is not full in \u55349?\u56478?.) Do the same for epimorphisms. Can you define a subcategory \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i n}{\i o}{\i n}{\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} of \u55349?\u56478? by restricting to morphisms that are not monomorphisms?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.4.a)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Mono\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let be {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) and {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i C}) be monomorphisms. Let us show that {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} is also a monomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z} be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?, and $\\alpha', \\alpha" \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{A\}\} (Z, A)$:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    (g \\circ f) \\circ \\alpha' = (g \\circ f) \\circ \\alpha''
        & = g \\circ (f \\circ \\alpha') = g \\circ (f \\circ \\alpha'') \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow f \\circ \\alpha' = f \\circ \\alpha'' \\text\{ because $g$ is mono\} \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow         \\alpha' =         \\alpha'' \\text\{ because $f$ is mono\}
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that the composition of 2 monomorphisms is always an monomorphism. We can thus make a subcategory. Taking all objects, properties, and homsets of \u55349?\u56478?, but restricting the homsets only to the monomorphisms, we know that this makes a new category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} since it is closed under composition, has identities (which are iso, and {\i a fortiori} mono) and associativity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.4.b)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Epi\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let be {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) and {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i C}) be epimorphisms. Let us show that {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} is also a epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z} be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?, and $\\beta', \\beta" \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (C, Z)$:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    \\beta' \\circ (g \\circ f) = \\beta'' \\circ (g \\circ f)
        & = (\\beta' \\circ g) \\circ f = (\\beta'' \\circ g) \\circ f \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow \\beta' \\circ g =  \\beta'' \\circ g \\text\{ because $f$ is epi\} \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow \\beta'         =  \\beta''         \\text\{ because $g$ is epi\}
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that the composition of 2 epimorphisms is always an epimorphism. We can thus make a subcategory. Taking all objects, properties, and homsets of \u55349?\u56478?, but restricting the homsets only to the epimorphisms, we know that this makes a new category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i e}{\i p}{\i i}} since it is closed under composition, has identities (which are iso, and {\i a fortiori} epi) and associativity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.4.c)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Nonmono and nonepi\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We could consider the fact that (TODO prove lol) we can\u8217't obtain a monomorphism from the composition of two non-monomorphisms (you need at least one monomorphism in the mix). However, the real problem is identities. Identities are iso, and thus mono. You can\u8217't make a category without identities, so there is no such \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i n}{\i o}{\i n}{\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}}. the same reasoning applies to \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i n}{\i o}{\i n}{\i e}{\i p}{\i i}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Give a concrete description of monomorphisms and epimorphisms in the category {\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} you constructed in Exercise 3.9. (Your answer will depend on the notion of morphism you defined in that exercise!)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We\u8217'll use our {\b C}{\b M}{\b S}{\b e}{\b t} construction, where elements of multisets consisted of a pair of the set-element and its count in the multiset.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We recall that in the way we formulated this, morphisms were just simple set functions on "(element, count)" pairs (i.e., returning any other "(element, count)" pair of the codomain). Let be a morphism of multisets {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}). Labelling the elements of the domain {\i A} as {\i a}{\sub {\i i}} and of the codomain {\i B} as {\i b}{\sub {\i j}} with {\i i}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i I}, {\i j}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i J}, and {\i I},\u8198?{\i J} any two indexing sets such that {\i c}{\i a}{\i r}{\i d}({\i A})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\i a}{\i r}{\i d}({\i I}) and {\i c}{\i a}{\i r}{\i d}({\i B})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\i a}{\i r}{\i d}({\i J}), we can see that {\i A} and {\i B} now just look like "normal" sets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now simply recycle the notion of injections and surjections. These form our monomorphisms and epimorphisms respectively.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Section 5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that a final object in a category \u55349?\u56478? is initial in the opposite category \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let \u55349?\u56478? be a category. Let \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} be the dual category on \u55349?\u56478?. Let {\i F} be a final object in \u55349?\u56478?. This means that for every object {\i Z} in \u55349?\u56478?, there is a single morphism from {\i Z} to {\i F}. We will call this morphism {\i f}{\sub {\i Z}} (respectively).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We remind how we defined composition in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}} as \u8902?, respecting: $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    & \\forall f \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (B, A) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, B), \\\\
    & \\forall g \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (C, B) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (B, C), \\\\
    & \\exists h \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}^\{op\}\} (C, A) = Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (A, C), \\\\
    & f \\star g \\coloneqq g \\circ f = h
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this case, we see that \u8704?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i O}{\i b}{\i j}(\u55349?\u56478?),\u8198?{\i f}{\sub {\i Z}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}}({\i F},\u8198?{\i Z})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i Z},\u8198?{\i F}). This implies that the homset {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}}({\i F},\u8198?{\i Z}) contains a single morphism, {\i f}{\sub {\i Z}}. This means that {\i F} is initial in \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i o}{\i p}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that \u8709? is the {\i unique} initial object in {\b Set}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First we will prove that it is initial, then that it is unique.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Initiality: we take an arbitrary set {\i Z} in {\b Set}. We wish to study $Hom_\{\\text\{\\textbf\{Set\}\}\}(\\emptyset, Z) = Z^\\emptyset$. We recall that functions (in category theory) are defined as "applications" / "mappings" are in traditional set theory (i.e., as a relation between sets where every antecedent in the domain has a singleton image in the codomain; the key point being that "no input has no result when passed through the function"). Let {\i I} be an initial element in {\b Set}. We write |{\i I}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n} and |{\i Z}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i m}. We know that |{\i Z}{\super {\i I}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i Z}|{\super |{\i I}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i m}{\super {\i n}}. For {\i I} to be initial, this is true if and only if {\i m}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?1 for all {\i m}, and so if and only if {\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?0. We recall that the empty set is the only set with |\u8709?|\u8196?=\u8196?0, therefore {\i I}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now this is already enough to prove unicity, but let us spell it out for pedagogy\u8217's sake.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unicity: We recall that two objects of {\b Set} are isomorphic if, and only if, there exists a bijection between them. This is equivalent to saying that two sets have the same cardinal. We once again recall that the empty set is the only set with |\u8709?|\u8196?=\u8196?0; there are no bijections relating to the empty set, other than its identity, the unique morphism in $Hom_\{\\text\{\\textbf\{Set\}\}\}(\\emptyset, \\emptyset)$ . Using proposition 5.4 (that terminal objects are unique up-to-isomorphism), we finally deduce that \u8709? is the unique initial object in {\b Set}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NB: the unique function in {\i Z}{\super \u8709?} is always the empty function.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that final objects are unique up to isomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us suppose we have a category \u55349?\u56478? with two final objects, {\i F}{\sub 1} and {\i F}{\sub 2}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For every object {\i A} of \u55349?\u56478? there is at least one element in {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i A}), namely the identity 1{\sub {\i A}}. If {\i F} is final, then there is a unique morphism {\i F}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i F}, which therefore must be the identity 1{\sub {\i F}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We assumed that {\i F}{\sub 1} and {\i F}{\sub 2} are both final in \u55349?\u56478?. Since {\i F}{\sub 1} is final, there is a unique morphism {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 1} in \u55349?\u56478?. Since {\i F}{\sub 2} is final, there is a unique morphism {\i g}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 2} in \u55349?\u56478?. Consider {\i f}{\i g}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 1} ; as observed, necessarily the composite {\i f}{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?1{\sub {\i F}{\sub 1}} since {\i F}{\sub 1} is final. By the same token {\i g}{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?1{\sub {\i F}{\sub 2}}. Thus {\i f} and {\i g} are inverses of each other, proving {\i f} is an isomorphism. Since there exists an isomorphism between {\i F}{\sub 1} and {\i F}{\sub 2}, {\i F}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?{\i F}{\sub 2}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What are initial and final objects in the category of "pointed sets" (Example 3.8)? Are they unique?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We recall that a pointed set is just a regular set with a special, identified point, and that the category of pointed sets {\b Set*} is built upon the same objects as {\b Set}, but where each object {\i A} in {\b Set} is multiplied into |{\i A}| copies of itself in {\b Set*} (one for each choice of special point; this implies that the empty set is not a part of {\b Set*}, since it has no point). Morphisms in {\b Set*} are set functions, but with the restriction of mapping the special point in the domain to the special point in the codomain.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Given this information, we will prove that the initial and final objects in {\b Set*} are the singleton sets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let ({\i O},\u8198?{\i o}) be a singleton set in {\b Set*}. Let {\i o} be the single element of {\i O}; it is necessarily also the special point, as there is no other choice. For any codomain ({\i Z},\u8198?{\i z}{\sub 0}) in {\b Set*}, the condition that "special points map to special points" restricts our choice of function to the unique function ({\i o},\u8198?{\i z}{\sub 0}), thus, {\i O} is initial. If {\i O} had more than one element, there would exist some {\i Z} (non-singletons) for which the other element would allow another degree of freedom (and thus {\i O} would not be initial).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, now studying {\i Z} as a domain and {\i O} as a codomain, we see that that only function from {\i Z} to {\i O} is (like in {\b Set}) the function which maps everything (including {\i Z}\u8217's special point) to {\i o}. Thus, {\i O} is final. If {\i O} had more than one element, there would similarly be many choices for any {\i Z} of cardinal \u8196?\u8805?\u8196?2, so long as the special point maps to the special point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Every singleton pointed set is both initial and final in {\b Set*} and is thus a zero object. These are also the only such pointed sets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What are the final objects in the category considered in \u167?5.3?\par}
