{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.11)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i A}, resp. {\i B}, be sets, endowed with equivalence relations \u8764?{\sub {\i A}}, resp. \u8764?{\sub {\i B}}. Define a relation \u8764? on {\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B} by setting ({\i a}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?({\i a}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 2})\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i a}{\sub 1}\u8764?{\sub {\i A}}{\i a}{\sub 2} and {\i b}{\sub 1}\u8764?{\sub {\i B}}{\i b}{\sub 2}. (This is immediately seen to be an equivalence relation.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use the universal property for quotients (\u167?5.3) to establish that there are functions ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?\u8197?\u8594?\u8197?{\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}}, and ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?\u8197?\u8594?\u8197?{\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab prove that ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?, with these two functions, satisfies the universal property for the product of {\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}} and {\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab conclude (without further work) that ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?\u8197?\u8196?\u8771?\u8196?({\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}})\u8197?\u215?\u8197?({\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}}).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 5.11.a)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, we remind the universal property for quotients. Given an equivalence relation \u8764? over a set {\i A}, there is a single map {\i \u960?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}/\u8764? such that, for any map {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} verifying {\i f}({\i a}{\sub 1})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i a}{\sub 2}) whenever {\i a}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i a}{\sub 2} (i.e., the morphism {\i f} is "well-defined" for the equivalence relation \u8764?), there exists a unique map $\\overline\{f\} : A/\\sim \\to Z$ such that $f = \\overline\{f\} \\circ \\pi$. This is summarized in the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now apply the universal property of products to obtain the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We then consider a well-defined map {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} (i.e., {\i f}({\i a}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 1})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i a}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 2}) whenever ({\i a}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?({\i a}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i b}{\sub 2})). We apply the universal property of quotients to the relation \u8764? defined over {\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}. We define the map {\i \u960?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764? as {\i \u960?}({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})\u8196?=\u8196?[({\i a},\u8198?{\i b})]{\sub \u8764?}. We define the map $\\overline\{f\} : (A \\times B)/\\sim \\; \\to \\; Z$ as $\\overline\{f\}([(a,b)]_\\sim) = f(a,b)$. We remind that such an {\i f} is unique, and that $\\overline\{f\} \\circ \\pi = f$.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We do a similar construction for {\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}} with {\i f}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}} with {\i f}{\sub {\i B}}. We can do so since these maps are also well-defined. Indeed, we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{array\}\{l\}
    \\left\\\{
    \\begin\{array\}\{l\}
        (a_1, b_1) \\sim (a_2, b_2) \\\\
        (a_1, b_1) \\sim (a_2, b_2) \\Rightarrow f(a_1, b_1) = f(a_2, b_2) \\\\
        f = f_A \\circ p_A \\\\
        f = f_B \\circ p_B
    \\end\{array\}
    \\right.
\\cr \\Rightarrow \\\\
    \\left\\\{
    \\begin\{array\}\{l\}
        a_1 \\sim_A a_2 \\text\{ and \} b_1 \\sim_B b_2 \\\\
        f_A(p_A(a_1, b_1)) = f_A(p_A(a_2, b_2)) \\\\
        f_B(p_B(a_1, b_1)) = f_B(p_B(a_2, b_2)) 
    \\end\{array\}
    \\right.
\\cr \\Rightarrow \\\\
    \\left\\\{
    \\begin\{array\}\{l\}
        f_A(a_1) = f_A(a_2) \\\\
        f_B(b_1) = f_B(b_2) 
    \\end\{array\}
    \\right.
\\end\{array\}$$\par}
