{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us recap a little what\u8217's in diagram a little, to show that it is a justified construction:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B} is a product, and so we may obtain {\i p}{\sub {\i A}}, {\i p}{\sub {\i B}}, {\i f}{\sub {\i A}}, and {\i f}{\sub {\i B}};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i f} is well-defined for the equivalence relation \u8764?, and so we may obtain $\\overline\{f\}$ and {\i \u960?};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i f}{\sub {\i A}} is well-defined for the equivalence relation \u8764?{\sub {\i A}}, and so we may obtain $\\overline\{f_A\}$ and {\i \u960?}{\sub {\i A}};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i f}{\sub {\i B}} is well-defined for the equivalence relation \u8764?{\sub {\i B}}, and so we may obtain $\\overline\{f_B\}$ and {\i \u960?}{\sub {\i B}};\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, we have the maps {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u960?}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i p}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}} and {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u960?}{\sub {\i B}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i p}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}}. {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i B}} are well-defined because they are compositions of well-defined maps. For {\i \u960?}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i \u960?}{\sub {\i B}}, we know that the projector and unique function part (of the universal property of quotients) are necessarily well-defined, otherwise they wouldn\u8217't compose to a well-defined map. As for {\i p}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i p}{\sub {\i B}}, they are well-defined because they are projections, and projections are always well-defined.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i B}} are well-defined, we can "quotient through" (i.e., use the universal property of quotient for) ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?.\par}
