{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using the fact that ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B}) is already a product, and studying maps {\i h}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i h}{\sub {\i B}} from {\i Z} into {\i A} and {\i B} respectively, we can make the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The internal parts of the diagram (except {\i h}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i h}{\sub {\i B}} which are arbitrary, all other arrows are unique morphisms) force {\i g}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i g}{\sub {\i B}} to commute with the rest of the diagram: any pairs of maps {\i g}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i g}{\sub {\i B}} that make the diagram commute must necessarily be constrained by the existing morphisms (as the composition of unique morphisms). Any choice of maps {\i g}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i g}{\sub {\i B}} must respect {\i g}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u960?}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i h}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i g}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u960?}{\sub {\i B}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i h}{\sub {\i B}}, for corresponding arbitrary (but inferred) {\i h}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i h}{\sub {\i B}}; said otherwise, maps {\i g}{\sub {\i A}} and {\i g}{\sub {\i B}} in this configuration can only exist if they make the diagram commute. Therefore, we have shown that ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764? satisfies the universal property of the product of {\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}} and {\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}}, and we have ({\i g}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i g}{\sub {\i B}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u960?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?({\i h}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i h}{\sub {\i B}}) (though it\u8217's not shown on the above diagram, in order to improve legibility).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 5.11.c)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We know that elements that verify a common universal property are terminal objects (of the same kind) in some comma category. Here, both ({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764? and (({\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}})\u8197?\u215?\u8197?({\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}})) are final objects in the bislice category $\\text\{\\textbf\{Set\}\}_\{A,B\}$. Since they are both final objects in the same category, they are isomorphic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: (({\i A}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?)\u8197?\u8771?\u8197?(({\i A}/\u8764?{\sub {\i A}})\u8197?\u215?\u8197?({\i B}/\u8764?{\sub {\i B}}))\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 5.12)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Define notions of fibered products and coproducts, as terminal objects of the categories \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}, {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}} considered in Example 3.10 (cf. also Exercise 3.11), by stating carefully the corresponding universal properties. As it happens, {\b Set} has both fibered products and coproducts. Define these objects \u8217'concretely\u8217', in terms of naive set theory. [II.3.9, III.6.10, III.6.11]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 5.12.a)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first define the fibered product (or "pullback"). We suggest the reader goes to check section 3.11.3 of this exercises solutions document for a refresher on the concept "fibered bislice category" \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. We will use the same notation, i.e., fixing two morphisms {\i \u945?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i C} and {\i \u946?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i C} (with common codomain) in a category \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means, for any generic object ({\i Z},\u8198?{\i f},\u8198?{\i g}) of \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}, we have the following diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first propose a candidate for what it means to be a "fibered product", which we will be able to show is a final object in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. A fibered product {\i P} of {\i A} and {\i B} over {\i C} in a category \u55349?\u56478? is an object {\i P} together with morphisms {\i p}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i P}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A} and {\i p}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i P}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B} such that for any object {\i Z} in \u55349?\u56478? and morphisms {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A} and {\i g}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B} such that {\i \u945?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u946?}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}, there exists a unique morphism {\i h}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i P} such that the following diagram commutes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will now show that this object {\i P} induces a terminal object in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}; this boils down to showing that ({\i P},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i B}}) is final in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. Let ({\i Z},\u8198?{\i f},\u8198?{\i g}) be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. A morphism {\i \u963?} from ({\i Z},\u8198?{\i f},\u8198?{\i g}) to ({\i P},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i B}}) is a "raising" of a morphism {\i h}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i P} such that {\i p}{\sub {\i A}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f} and {\i p}{\sub {\i B}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}. This raising {\i \u963?} is unique if and only if {\i h} is unique. Since {\i P} is presupposed to verify the universal property, such an {\i h}, if it exists, is indeed unique. Therefore, ({\i P},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i B}}) is final ({\i a fortiori} terminal) in \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 5.12.b)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now define the fibered coproduct (or "pushout"). We suggest the reader goes to check section 3.11.4 of this exercises solutions document for a refresher on the "fibered bicoslice category" {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. We will use the same notation, i.e., fixing two morphisms {\i \u945?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A} and {\i \u946?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B} (with common domain) in a category \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
