{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In {\b Set}, the fibered coproduct (pushout) of ({\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i A}) and ({\i \u946?},\u8198?{\i B}) over {\i C} is a special quotient of the disjoint union {\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B} that registers some extra information, pertaining to the functions {\i \u945?} and {\i \u946?}. We write this object as {\i P}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i A}\u8852?{\sub {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i C},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i A}\u8852?{\sub {\i C}}{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B})/\u8764?, where \u8764? is an equivalence relation defined as \u8764?\u8197?\u8196?:=\u8196?{\i c}{\i l}{\sub {\i e}{\i q}}({\i R}), the equivalence closure of the relation {\i R}\u8196?=\u8196?\{((0,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(1,\u8198?{\i b}))\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B})\u8197?\u215?\u8197?({\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B})\u8197?\u8739?\u8197?\u8707?{\i c}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i C},\u8198?{\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u945?}({\i c}) and {\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u946?}({\i c})\} (i.e., two elements are equivalent if they are both the output of some common {\i c}, or if there is any chain of such equivalences between them).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (We remind that the equivalence closure, if elements of the set are seen as vertices and the relation pairs as edges of a graph, can be thought of, visually, as "completing the cliques" of each connected component in the graph, including self-loops; hence the idea that if there is any path between two elements, then they are equivalent and should be directly linked. We also remind that this corresponds uniquely to a partition of the set; the elements of which, called cosets, are what allow us to do an algebraic quotient.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fibered coproduct is the set {\i P} obtained by taking the disjoint union {\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B} and identifying {\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A} with {\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B} if there exists {\i c}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i C} such that {\i \u945?}({\i c})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a} and {\i \u946?}({\i c})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b} (and all identifications that follow to keep the equality relation an equivalence relation). There is no more concrete of a definition than this; it really boils down to identifying elements with a common preimage element through {\i \u945?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}({\i A}) and {\i \u946?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}({\i B}) in {\i C}, via an equivalence relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us show this is the case with a simple example. We will keep the elements of {\i A} and {\i B} distinct in order to remove the visual clutter that comes with the (0,\u8198?...) and (1,\u8198?...) of the general disjoint union.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\}, {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i w},\u8198?{\i x},\u8198?{\i y},\u8198?{\i z}\}, and {\i C}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i l},\u8198?{\i m},\u8198?{\i n}\}. We define {\i \u945?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A} as \{({\i l},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i n},\u8198?2)\}, and {\i \u946?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B} as \{({\i l},\u8198?{\i x}),\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i y}),\u8198?({\i n},\u8198?{\i z})\}. We have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i \u945?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{1\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i l},\u8198?{\i m}\} and {\i \u946?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i x}\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i l}\}, so 1\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i x};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i \u945?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{1\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i l},\u8198?{\i m}\} and {\i \u946?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i y}\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i m}\}, so 1\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i y}, and by closure, 1\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i x}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i y};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i \u945?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{2\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i n}\} and {\i \u946?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i z}\})\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i n}\}, so 2\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i z};\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\i \u945?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{3\})\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709? and {\i \u946?}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}(\{{\i w}\})\u8196?=\u8196?\u8709?, so you might think that 3\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i w}, however, since there is no {\i c}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i C} such that {\i \u945?}({\i c})\u8196?=\u8196?3 and {\i \u946?}({\i c})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i w}, we have 3\u8196?\u8769?\u8196?{\i w};\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This information corresponds to the following partition of {\i A}\u8197?\u8852?\u8197?{\i B}: \{\{1,\u8198?{\i x},\u8198?{\i y}\},\u8198?\{2,\u8198?{\i z}\},\u8198?\{3\},\u8198?\{{\i w}\}\}. The fibered coproduct is then:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{array\}\{lll\}
P &=& (A \\sqcup B) / \\sim \\\\
  &=& \\\{1,2,3,w,x,y,z\\\} / \\sim \\\\
  &=& \\\{\\\{1,x,y\\\}, \\\{2,z\\\}, \\\{3\\\}, \\\{w\\\}\\\} \\\\
  &=& \\\{[1], [2], [3], [w]\\\}
\\end\{array\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A way to verify this is to verify that each equivalence class is disjoint, and that all pairs of elements within an equivalence class are related by \u8764? (by applying {\i \u945?} or {\i \u946?} where appropriate and drawing the graph of the relation).\par}
