{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Write a careful proof that every group is the group of isomorphisms of a groupoid. In particular, every group is the group of automorphisms of some object in some category.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us first remind the definition of a groupoid: a groupoid is a category in which every morphism is an isomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Side-note: by "group of isomorphisms", what Aluffi rather meant is "group of isomorphisms (of the single object) in a groupoid (that has a single object)". Otherwise, with multiple objects, things fail: for example, there are multiple identities, one per object, not universally applicable to each object. This is precisely why the notion of "groupoid" was invented, to extend the notion of group in such a way.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let ({\i G},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) be a group, i.e., some form of algebraic structure with a set of elements {\i G} and a binary operation \u8901? which is associative, unitary, and invertible. We want to show that there exists a groupoid \u55349?\u56478? such that ({\i G},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is the group of isomorphisms of \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us define \u55349?\u56478? as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There is a single object {\i X} in \u55349?\u56478?, and its elements are the elements of {\i G} (we could call {\i X} "{\i G}", of course, but we\u8217'll be distinct for pedagogy\u8217's sake). Our goal is to prove that {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}({\i X},\u8198?{\i X}) is isomorphic to {\i G}, and thus is itself a group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For any element {\i g} of {\i X}, there is a unique morphism {\i f}{\sub {\i g}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}({\i X},\u8198?{\i X}) such that \u8704?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i X},\u8198?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i g}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Composition of morphisms is defined as follows: {\i f}{\sub {\i a}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub {\i b}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?({\i b}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}))\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?({\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b})\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b}}\u8197?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There is an identity morphism {\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i X}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i e}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}), with {\i e} the identity element of {\i G}, and \u8704?{\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}({\i X},\u8198?{\i X}),\u8198?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i X}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i X}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It is immediate to see that these morphisms are associative since ({\i G},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is associative. Take {\i f}{\sub {\i a}}, {\i f}{\sub {\i b}}, and {\i f}{\sub {\i c}} in {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}({\i X},\u8198?{\i X}), for {\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i X}: ({\i f}{\sub {\i a}}{\i f}{\sub {\i b}}){\i f}{\sub {\i c}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?(({\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b})\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i c}){\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?({\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?({\i b}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i c})){\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub {\i a}}({\i f}{\sub {\i b}}{\i f}{\sub {\i c}}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Every such morphism has an inverse, namely, {\i f}{\sub {\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}) which by definition of a group necessarily exists. It is easy to verify that {\i f}{\sub {\i g}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\sub {\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i g}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i X}})\u8197?.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a groupoid, because, it is a category (composition, associativity, identity) where every morphism is an isomorphism (every morphism has an inverse), and the group of isomorphisms of (the single-object category) \u55349?\u56478?, here {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}({\i X},\u8198?{\i X}), is precisely isomorphic to ({\i G},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?).\par}
