{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Consider the \u8217'sets of numbers\u8217' listed in \u167?1.1, and decide which are made into groups by conventional operations such as + and \u8901?. Even if the answer is negative (for example: (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is not a group), see if variations on the definition of these sets lead to groups (for example, (\u8477?{\super *},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is a group, cf. \u167?1.4). [\u167?1.2]\par}
