{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \u8474?: (\u8474?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) is a group, but (\u8474?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is not because it is not fully invertible (e.g., 0\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?1 has no solution in \u8474?). However, remove 0 from (\u8474?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) and it becomes a group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \u8477?: (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) is a group, but (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is not because it is not fully invertible (e.g., 0\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?1 has no solution in \u8477?). However, remove 0 from (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) and it becomes a group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \u8450?: (\u8450?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) is a group, but (\u8450?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) is not because it is not fully invertible (e.g., 0\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?1 has no solution in \u8450?). However, remove 0 from (\u8450?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) and it becomes a group.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that (\u8469?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) is not a group, but (\u8484?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?), (\u8474?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?), (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?), and (\u8450?,\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) are all groups. Also, (\u8469?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), (\u8484?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), (\u8474?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), (\u8477?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), and (\u8450?,\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) are not groups. However, (\u8474?{\super *},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), (\u8477?{\super *},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?), and (\u8450?{\super *},\u8198?\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?) are groups.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that ({\i g}{\i h}){\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} for all elements {\i g},\u8198?{\i h} of a group {\i G}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ({\i g}{\i h})({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}({\i h}{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\i e}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} ({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})({\i g}{\i h})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}({\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}){\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i e}{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, {\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} is a 2-sided inverse for {\i g}{\i h}, and since the inverse of an element in a group is unique, ({\i g}{\i h}){\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i g}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} for all elements {\i g} of a group {\i G}; prove that {\i G} is commutative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If {\i f}{\i o}{\i r}{\i a}{\i l}{\i l}{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G},\u8198?{\i g}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}, then every element is its own inverse, i.e., multiply by {\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} on the left (or right), and we have \u8704?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G},\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}. Let be {\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}. Then, we have {\i b}{\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i b}{\i a}){\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i b}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}{\i b}, which is the definition of commutativity. Therefore, {\i G} is commutative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The \u8217'multiplication table\u8217' of a group is an array compiling the results of all multiplications {\i g}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i h} (with the value on each row being the left operand, and the value on each column being the right operand; of course the table depends on the order in which the elements are listed in the top row and leftmost column). Prove that every row and every column of the multiplication table of a group contains all elements of the group exactly once (like Sudoku diagrams!).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Another way to phrase this question is "prove that every element of the group can be reached in a single operation from any other (on the left, or on the right, both work)". Written in function notation, this means:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G},\u8198?\u8707?{\i g}{\sub {\i r}},\u8198?{\i g}{\sub {\i c}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub {\i r}}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a} and {\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub {\i c}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For every element {\i a}, we can reach the identity with {\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} (on either side). Every element {\i b} can then be reached from the identity by multiplying it (on either side). We just have to pick the same side both times to find either {\i g}{\sub {\i r}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} and {\i g}{\sub {\i c}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b}. Since the group is closed under "multiplication", both these elements are guaranteed to exist.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This implies that every row and every column of the multiplication table of a group contains all elements of the group exactly once, since any element can be reached in a single multiplication (i.e., there as many possible inputs (1 sided operand) as possible outputs (i.e., applying an operand is an injection) and all outputs are reached (it\u8217's also a surjection)). This also implies that the multiplication table is a "Latin square", which is a square array of |{\i G}| symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that there is only one possible multiplication table for {\i G} if {\i G} has exactly 1, 2, or 3 elements. Analyze the possible multiplication tables for groups with exactly 4 elements, and show that there are two distinct tables, up to reordering the elements of {\i G}. Use these tables to prove that all groups with \u8196?\u8804?\u8196?4 elements are commutative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These multiplication tables are usually called "Cayley tables".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 1.6.a) 1-element group\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For the unique table of the trivial group (only 1 element); {\i e} is necessarily its own inverse. Some examples of this group are (\{0\},\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) or (\{1\},\u8198?\u8197?\u215?\u8197?). This group is trivially commutative.\par}
