{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the identity and respective inverses commute, all that\u8217's left is to check the commutativity of the self-inverse element {\i a} with both of the mutual-inverses elements {\i b} and {\i c}. In this case, it is because there is "only one option left" in the Latin square that we get commutativity: e.g., {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b} cannot equal {\i e} since they are not inverses, cannot equal {\i a} since {\i b}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i e}, cannot equal {\i b} since {\i a}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i e}, so we must have {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}. The same reasoning can be applied to {\i b}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a} to get {\i c} (hence {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a}). With a relabelling, we apply this reasoning to {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i c} to get {\i b} and to {\i c}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a} to get {\i b} (hence {\i a}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i c}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i a}). With this, we have proven commutativity.\par}
