{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With that, we\u8217've proven that all groups of order \u8196?\u8804?\u8196?4 are commutative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Note that the commutativity can also be "seen" in all these tables by the fact that they are their own transpose.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.7)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove Corollary 1.11: Let {\i g} be an element of finite order, and let {\i n}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. Then {\i g}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?\u8707?{\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i k}|{\i g}| ({\i n} is a multiple of |{\i g}|).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By Lemma 1.10, if {\i g}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}, then |{\i g}| divides {\i n}. Therefore, \u8707?{\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i k}|{\i g}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For the converse, we suppose \u8707?{\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i k}|{\i g}|. By definition of the order of a group element, {\i g}{\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}, so {\i g}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super |{\i g}|{\i k}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i g}{\super |{\i g}|}){\super {\i k}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}{\super {\i k}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}. Hence, {\i g}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.8)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i G} be a finite group, with exactly one element {\i f} of order 2. Prove that {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}}{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I had some trouble, so I checked online and found this, meaning that the group probably needs to be not just finite but also abelian:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/2550052/let-g-be-a-finite-abelian-group-with-exactly-one-element-of-order-2-denoted\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (A couple of notes: since {\i f}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}, it also means that {\i f} is the only self-inverse (involution) in {\i G}. Also, the order of operation is not given: this gives us a hint that the property ({\i \u928?}{\sub {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}}\u8197?{\i g}){\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} does not rely on the order of operations.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since {\i f} is the only element which is a self-inverse of order 2, {\i e} is the only self-inverse of order 1, we have that for all other elements a {\i g} in {\i G}, {\i g} is not its own inverse. This means that the product of all elements of {\i G} is a product of pairs of inverses, which cancel out to the identity (given commutativity), except for the self-inverse {\i f} which remains. Therefore, {\i \u928?}{\sub {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}}{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.9)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i G} be a finite group, of order {\i n}, and let {\i m} be the number of elements {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G} of order exactly 2. Prove that {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i m} is odd. Deduce that if {\i n} is even then {\i G} necessarily contains elements of order 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (This would be trivial if we could use Lagrange\u8217's theorem.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let us consider the set of elements of {\i G} of order 2, {\i M}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}\u8197?\u8739?\u8197?|{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?2\}, with |{\i M}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i m}. We know that for all {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i M}, {\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}. This means that {\i M} is the set of self-inverse elements (not counting {\i e}). This means that {\i G}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i M} contains only pairs of inverses (with {\i k} such pairs), and the self-inverse {\i e}, so has its cardinal can be written |{\i G}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i M}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i G}|\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?|{\i M}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i m}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1, i.e., it is an odd number.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If |{\i G}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n} is even, then it can be written as 2{\i l} for some {\i l}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469? with {\i l}\u8196?>\u8196?{\i k}. Consequently |{\i M}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i G}|\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?({\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i m})\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i l}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?(2{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1)\u8196?=\u8196?2({\i l}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i k})\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1, which is odd, and \u8196?>\u8196?0 since {\i l}\u8196?>\u8196?{\i k}. Therefore, {\i G} necessarily contains at least 1 element of order 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.10)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose the order of {\i g} is odd. What can you say about the order of {\i g}{\super 2} ?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We write |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1 since it is odd.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?({\i g}{\super 2}){\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i g}{\super |{\i g}|}){\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By Corollary 1.11, ({\i g}{\super 2}){\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i g}{\super 2}){\super 2{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?\u8707?{\i l}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469?,\u8198?|{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1\u8196?=\u8196?{\i l}|{\i g}{\super 2}|. Since |{\i g}| is odd, both {\i l} and |{\i g}{\super 2}| must be odd.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.11)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that for all {\i g},\u8198?{\i h} in a group {\i G}, |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i h}{\i g}|. (Hint: prove that |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}| for all {\i a},\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i a},\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{array\}\{ll\}
(aga^\{-1\})^\{|g|\} &= (aga^\{-1\})(aga^\{-1\})...(aga^\{-1\}) \\\\
                 &= ag(a^\{-1\}a)g(a^\{-1\}a)g...ga^\{-1\} \\\\
                 &= ag^\{|g|\}a^\{-1\} \\\\
                 &= aea^\{-1\} \\\\
                 &= (aa^\{-1\}) \\\\
                 &= e
\\end\{array\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By Lemma 1.10, |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}| is a divisor of |{\i g}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By definition, ({\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}. However, similarly to above, ({\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}{\i g}{\super |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}. So we have {\i a}{\i g}{\super |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}; then, multiplying on the left by {\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} and right by {\i a}, we get {\i g}{\super |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}. By Lemma 1.10, |{\i g}| is a divisor of |{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the divisibility relation is an order relation (antisymmetric), the only time two numbers can be mutually divisors of each other is if we\u8217're in the reflexive case (i.e., they are equal). Therefore, |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i a}{\i g}{\i a}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Applying this identity to the elements {\i g}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i g}{\i h} with {\i a}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i h}, we have |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|({\i h})({\i g}{\i h})({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1})|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i h}{\i g}|\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.12)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the group of invertible 2\u8197?\u215?\u8197?2 matrices, consider $g = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\}$, $h = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\}$. Verify that |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?4, |{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?3, and |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?\u8734?. [\u167?1.6]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We remind call that the neutral element for 2D square matrix multiplication is the identity matrix {\i I}{\sub 2}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$g^2 = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\}
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\} -1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$g^4 = (g^2)^2
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\} -1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} -1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\}  1 & 0 \\\\ 0 &  1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
    = I_2$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$h^2 = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\} 
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\} -1 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$h^3 = h^2 h
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\} -1 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
    = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
    = I_2$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will now prove by induction that $\\forall n \\geq 1, P(n): (gh)^n = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & n \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\}$.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Initiatialization:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$gh = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & -1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
   = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 True for {\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inheritance:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We suppose {\i P}({\i n}) true for a specific {\i n}, we\u8217'll show that {\i P}({\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1) holds.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$(gh)^\{n+1\} = (gh)^n(gh)
       = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & n \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\} \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\}
       = \\begin\{pmatrix\} 1 & (n+1) \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{pmatrix\}$$ Therefore {\i P}({\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1) is true. This prives inheritance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By induction, {\i P}({\i n}) is true for all {\i n}\u8196?\u8805?\u8196?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, there exists no {\i n}\u8196?\u8805?\u8196?1 such that ({\i g}{\i h}){\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i I}{\sub 2}, hence |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?\u8734?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.13)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Give an example showing that |{\i g}{\i h}| is not necessarily equal to lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|), even if {\i g} and {\i h} commute. [\u167?1.6, 1.14]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We take the 6-hour clock {\i Z}{\sub 6}, and {\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?[3]{\sub 6}, the equivalence class of 3 modulo 6. We have {\i g}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?[3]{\sub 6}\u8197?+\u8197?[3]{\sub 6}\u8196?=\u8196?[6]{\sub 6}\u8196?=\u8196?[0]{\sub 6}, so |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?2 and |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?1. However, lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)\u8196?=\u8196?2\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?1\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 1.14)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a counterpoint to Exercise 1.13, prove that if {\i g} and {\i h} commute, and gcd(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)\u8196?=\u8196?1 (they are coprime), then |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}||{\i h}|. (Hint: let {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}|; then {\i g}{\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}. What can you say about this element?) [\u167?1.6, 1.15, \u167?IV.2.5]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, we remark that for any {\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G}, {\i x}{\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?{\i e}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}, so |{\i x}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We have that gcd(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)\u8196?=\u8196?1, and we know that |{\i g}||{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?gcd(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|) so we have |{\i g}||{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}|. Then, given that ({\i g}{\i h}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}, that {\i g} and {\i h} commute, and multiplying by ({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}} on the right of both side, we have ({\i g}{\i h}){\super {\i N}}({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super {\i N}}{\i h}{\super {\i N}}({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super {\i N}}({\i h}{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}. Therefore, {\i g}{\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now study {\i f}{\super |{\i g}|} and {\i f}{\super |{\i h}|}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We have {\i f}{\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i g}{\super {\i N}}){\super |{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super {\i N}|{\i g}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, {\i e}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\super |{\i h}|}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super |{\i h}|}\u8196?=\u8196?(({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super |{\i h}|}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?(({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}){\super |{\i h}|}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}{\super |{\i h}|} (by our initial remark).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, {\i M}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i f}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\super {\i N}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i h}{\super {\i N}}| divides both |{\i g}| and |{\i h}|. Since |{\i g}| and |{\i h}| are coprime, {\i M}\u8196?=\u8196?1. Therefore {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}, so {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}| is a multiple of |{\i g}| and {\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}){\super {\i N}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} so {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}| is a multiple of |{\i h}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i h}|. Since |{\i g}| and |{\i h}| are coprime, we can further say that |{\i g}{\i h}| is a multiple of their LCM/product |{\i g}||{\i h}| (using, for example, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using Proposition 1.14 (i.e, if {\i g}{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}{\i g}, then |{\i g}{\i h}| divides lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)), we can also tell that {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}| divides lcm(|{\i g}|,|{\i h}|)\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}||{\i h}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Putting both results together using the antisymmetry of the divisibility relation, we have {\i N}\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}||{\i h}|.\par}
