{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i G} be a commutative group, and let {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G} be an element of maximal finite order: that is, such that if {\i h}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G} has finite order then |{\i h}|\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?|{\i g}|. Prove that in fact if {\i h} has finite order in {\i G} then |{\i h}| divides |{\i g}|. (Hint: argue by contradiction. If |{\i h}| is finite but does not divide |{\i g}|, then there is a prime integer {\i p} such that |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i m}}{\i r}, |{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i n}}{\i s}, with {\i r} and {\i s} relatively prime to {\i p}, and {\i m}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i n}. Use Exercise 1.14 (the fact that the order of the product of two elements with coprime order is equal to the product of their orders) to compute the order of {\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}}{\i h}{\super {\i s}}.) [\u167?2.1, 4.11, IV.6.15]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We suppose that |{\i h}| is finite but does not divide |{\i g}|. Using the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, if |{\i h}| doesn\u8217't divide |{\i g}|, then it has at least one prime factor that |{\i g}| does not have. Then, there is a prime integer {\i p} such that |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i m}}{\i r}, |{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i n}}{\i s}, with {\i r} and {\i s} (potentially composite), both independently coprime with {\i p}, and 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i m}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i n}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We know from exercise 1.14 that if 2 elements {\i a} and {\i b} commute (which is always the case in a commutative group like here), if the two elements have coprime order, then |{\i a}{\i b}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i a}||{\i b}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The order |{\i x}{\super {\i k}}| of {\i x}{\super {\i k}}, is $\\frac\{|x|\}\{\\text\{gcd\}(|x|, k)\}$, assuming |{\i x}| is finite (Proposition 1.13).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We study {\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}}{\i h}{\super {\i s}}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The order of {\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}} is $\\frac\{|g|\}\{\\text\{gcd\}(|g|, p^m)\} = \\frac\{p^m r\}\{p^m\} = r$ because {\i p}{\super {\i m}} divides |{\i g}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, the order of {\i h}{\super {\i s}} is $|h|/\\text\{gcd\}(|h|, s) = \\frac\{p^n s\}\{s\} = p^n$ because {\i s} divides |{\i h}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since {\i G} is a commutative group, {\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}} and {\i h}{\super {\i s}} commute. By Exercise 1.14, |{\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}}{\i h}{\super {\i s}}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i g}{\super {\i p}{\super {\i m}}}||{\i h}{\super {\i s}}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i n}}{\i r}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i m}}({\i p}{\super {\i m}}{\i r})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i p}{\super {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i m}}|{\i g}|\u8196?>\u8196?|{\i g}|.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a contradiction with the fact that |{\i g}| has {\i maximal} finite order. Therefore, our assumption that |{\i h}| does not divide |{\i g}| must be false.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: if {\i G} is an abelian group, {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G} has maximal finite order, and {\i h}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i G} has finite order in {\i G}, then |{\i h}| divides |{\i g}|.\par}
