{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One can associate an {\i n}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i n} matrix {\i M}{\sub {\i \u963?}} with a permutation {\i \u963?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i n}}, by letting the entry at ({\i i},\u8198?{\i \u963?}({\i i})) be 1, and letting all other entries be 0. For example, the matrix corresponding to the permutation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\sigma =
    \\begin\{pmatrix\}
        1 & 2 & 3 \\\\
        3 & 2 & 1
    \\end\{pmatrix\}
\\in S_3$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Aluffi seems to have made a mistake, writing 312 instead of 321, so we fixed it here)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 would be\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$M_\\sigma =
    \\begin\{pmatrix\}
        0 & 0 & 1 \\\\
        0 & 1 & 0 \\\\
        1 & 0 & 0
    \\end\{pmatrix\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that, with this notation, {\i M}{\sub {\i \u963?}{\i \u964?}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i M}{\sub {\i \u963?}}{\i M}{\sub {\i \u964?}} for all {\i \u963?},\u8198?{\i \u964?}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i n}} , where the product on the right is the ordinary product of matrices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first notice that we can write down the formal expression of {\i M}{\sub {\i \u963?}}, in the dummy Kronecker delta style, is just the permutation of the columns of the identity {\i I}: here {\i M}{\sub {\i \u963?}}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i I}{\sub {\i i}{\i \u963?}({\i j})}){\sub {\i i},\u8198?{\i j}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?[[1,\u8198?{\i n}]]}. Therefore, using the Kronecker delta to match the indices, we have that the product of two matrices\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
M_\\sigma M_\\tau
&= (I_\{i \\; \\sigma(j)\})_\{ij\} \\cdot (I_\{i \\; \\tau(j)\})_\{ij\} \\\\
&= \\sum_\{j=1\}^n \\delta_\{i \\; \\sigma(j)\} \\cdot \\delta_\{j \\; \\tau(k)\} \\quad \\text\{($\\ast$)\}\\\\
&= (I_\{i \\; \\sigma(\\tau(k))\})_\{ik\} \\\\
&= M_\{\\sigma\\tau\}
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 as desired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (*): each term acts a Kronecker delta, in particular, the second term is non-null iff {\i j}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u964?}({\i k}), which acts as our replacement in the following line.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that if {\i d}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i n} then {\i S}{\sub {\i n}} contains elements of order {\i d}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will use strong induction on {\i n}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Initialization: for {\i S}{\sub 1}, the case is trivial (the identity element has order 1). For {\i S}{\sub 2}, we saw that this group was necessarily isomorphic to \u8484?{\sub 2}, which has the identity, and one element of order 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Heredity: For some {\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8469?, we suppose that the property is true for all {\i d}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i k}. We will show that it is true for {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1. Keeping the last element fixed, we see that the portion of {\i S}{\sub {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1} that can permute is isomorphic to {\i S}{\sub {\i k}}: by our hypothesis, it thus has elements of order {\i d} for all {\i d}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i k}. We just need to show that we can find an element of order {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1 in {\i S}{\sub {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We take the a cyclic permutation of all elements (which acts like a Caesar cypher of distance parameter 1): each {\i i}\u8196?>\u8196?1 is mapped to to {\i i}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1, and 1 is mapped to {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1. Let us prove that this permutation has order {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that the cycle of this permutation is 1\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i k}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i k}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u8230?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?1, which has length {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now show that the order of any cyclic permutation is the length of the cycle. Let be {\i S}{\sub {\i n}} a permutation group and {\i C} a cycle in it, generated by a permutation {\i \u963?}. We denote elements of the cycle as {\i c}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i c}{\sub 2},\u8198?\u8230?,\u8198?{\i c}{\sub {\i m}} with {\i m}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i n} such that the cycle can be expressed as {\i c}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i c}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?\u8230?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i c}{\sub {\i m}}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i c}{\sub 1}. We have that \u8704?{\i j}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?[[1,\u8198?{\i m}]],\u8198?{\i \u963?}{\super 0}({\i c}{\sub {\i j}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub {\i j}}, trivially. Then, we have {\i \u963?}{\super 1}({\i c}{\sub {\i j}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub [{\i j}]{\sub {\i m}}\u8197?+\u8197?1} (meaning {\i j} modulo {\i m} plus 1), and so on. We see that {\i \u963?}{\super {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}({\i c}{\sub {\i j}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub [{\i j}]{\sub {\i m}}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}, and {\i \u963?}{\super {\i n}}({\i c}{\sub {\i j}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub [{\i j}]{\sub {\i m}}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub [{\i j}]{\sub {\i m}}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i c}{\sub {\i j}}. Therefore, the order of {\i \u963?} is {\i m}, the length of the cycle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, we have shown that {\i S}{\sub {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1} has cyclic permutations of length {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1, and thus elements of order {\i k}\u8197?+\u8197?1, which completes the proof.\par}
