{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Describe generators and relations for all dihedral groups {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}}. (Hint: let {\i x} be the reflection about a line through the center of a regular {\i n}-gon and a vertex, and let {\i y} be counterclockwise rotation by 2{\i \u960?}/{\i n}. The group {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}} will be generated by {\i x} and {\i y}, subject to three relations. To see that these relations really determine {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}}, use them to show that any product {\i x}{\super {\i i}{\sub 1}}{\i y}{\super {\i i}{\sub 2}}{\i x}{\super {\i i}{\sub 3}}{\i y}{\super {\i i}{\sub 4}}\u8230? equals {\i x}{\super {\i i}}{\i y}{\super {\i j}} for some {\i i}, {\i j} with 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i i}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?1, 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i j}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i n}.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Two of the relations are very easy to see: {\i x}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} (for any axial symmetry flip {\i x}) and {\i y}{\super {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e} (for any {\i n}-rotation {\i y}). Another hint (given at the bottom of page 52, as done on an imaginary pentagon) tells us to study {\i y}{\i x}{\i y}{\i x} (hinting that it is equal to {\i e}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first note that {\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x} since any axial symmetry is an involution. Geometrically speaking, we can see that the operation {\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i y}{\i x} is a rotation by 2{\i \u960?}/{\i n} in the opposite direction to {\i y}. We can thus write {\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i y}{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i y}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}, and thus {\i y}{\i x}{\i y}{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i e}. This is our 3rd relation, which we can also rewrite as {\i y}{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}{\i y}{\super \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x}{\i y}{\super {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can now write any element of {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}} as {\i x}{\super {\i i}}{\i y}{\super {\i j}} for 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i i}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?1, 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i j}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i n}. Any power of {\i x} reduces to {\i e} (if the exponent is even) or {\i x} (if the exponent is odd), any power {\i k} of {\i y} reduces to {\i y}{\super [{\i k}]{\sub {\i n}}}, and any {\i y}{\i x} term sandwiched between an {\i x} and a {\i y} terms can be changed to {\i x}{\i y}{\super {\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1} in order to reduce with the {\i x} (or {\i e}) on the left, and the {\i y}{\super [{\i k}]{\sub {\i n}}} on the right. Through this algorithm, we can always get an element of the form {\i x}{\super {\i i}}{\i y}{\super {\i j}} for 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i i}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?1, 0\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i j}\u8196?<\u8196?{\i n}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For every positive integer {\i n} construct a group containing two elements {\i g}, {\i h} such that |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?2, |{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?2, and |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n}. (Hint: for {\i n}\u8196?>\u8196?1, {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}} will do.) [\u167?1.6]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can take the dihedral group {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}}, and take the reflection {\i x} and the rotation {\i y} (as defined in the previous exercise). Taking {\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x} and {\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x}{\i y}, we have that |{\i g}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i x}|\u8196?=\u8196?2 (by the first relation), |{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i x}{\i y}|\u8196?=\u8196?2 (by the third relation) and |{\i g}{\i h}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i x}{\i x}{\i y}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i y}|\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n} (by the second relation).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As for the case with {\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1, we take the group (\u8484?{\sub 2},\u8198?\u8197?+\u8197?) and set {\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i h}\u8196?=\u8196?1; their sum is the identity 0, which has order 1 (technically, to stay in the {\i D}{\sub 2{\i n}} picture, this is isomorphic to the group of symmtries of a "2-gon", a line, with either the identity, or a flip across its mediatrix).\par}
