{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Verify carefully that \u8217'congruence mod {\i n}\u8217' is an equivalence relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We define the relation \u8764? as \u8704?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i b}\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?\u8707?{\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i k}{\i n}. We will show that this relation is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reflexivity:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?0\u8196?=\u8196?0\u8197?\u8901?\u8197?{\i n}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i a}\u8196?\u8764?\u8196?{\i a}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Symmetry:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
\\forall a, b \\in \\mathbb\{Z\}, a \\sim b
&\\Leftrightarrow \\exists k \\in \\mathbb\{Z\}, a - b = kn \\\\
&\\Leftrightarrow \\exists k \\in \\mathbb\{Z\}, b - a = -kn \\\\
&\\Leftrightarrow b \\sim a
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Transitivity: $$\\begin\{aligned\}
\\forall a, b, c \\in \\mathbb\{Z\}, (a \\sim b) \\land (b \\sim c)
&\\Leftrightarrow \\exists k, l \\in \\mathbb\{Z\}, (a - b = kn) \\land (b - c = ln) \\\\
&\\Leftrightarrow a - c = (a - b) + (b - c) = (k + l)n \\\\
&\\Leftrightarrow a \\sim c
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, the relation \u8764? is an equivalence relation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.10)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? contains precisely {\i n} elements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each element of \u8484? can be written uniquely as {\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i k}{\i n} with {\i m}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?[[0,\u8198?{\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1]] and {\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. Therefore, we have {\i n} possible values for {\i m}. Because congruence modulo {\i n} equates two numbers in \u8484? if their difference is a multiple of {\i n}, we have that {\i m} and {\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i k}{\i n} are equivalent. Therefore, we can consider an equivalence class associated with {\i m} to contain all elements of the form {\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i k}{\i n}. Since we have precisely {\i n} such equivalence classes, \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? contains precisely {\i n} elements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.11)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that the square of every odd integer is congruent to 1 modulo 8. [\u167?VII.5.1]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We write an odd integer as 2{\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1 for {\i n}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. We have that (2{\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1){\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?4{\i n}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?4{\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1\u8196?=\u8196?4({\i n}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i n})\u8197?+\u8197?1. We can see that {\i n}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i n} is always even, because: if {\i n} is even, then {\i n}{\super 2} is even, and {\i n} is even, so their sum is even; and if {\i n} is odd, then {\i n}{\super 2} is odd, and {\i n} is odd, so their sum is even. Therefore, we can write {\i n}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i m} for some {\i m}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?, and thus (2{\i n}\u8197?+\u8197?1){\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?8{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?1, which is congruent to 1 modulo 8.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.12)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that there are no integers {\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c} such that {\i a}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i c}{\super 2}. (Hint: by studying the equation [{\i a}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?[{\i b}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3[{\i c}]{\sub 4}{\super 2} in \u8484?/4\u8484?, show that {\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c} would all have to be even. Letting {\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i k}, {\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i l}, {\i c}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i m}, you would have {\i k}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i l}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i m}{\super 2}. What\u8217's wrong with that?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can write {\i a}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i c}{\super 2} as {\i a}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i c}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?4{\i k} with {\i k}\u8196?=\u8196?0. Any solution to the first equation must thus respect the properties of the second equation. We study these properties by looking at the equation modulo 4.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
[a]^2_4 + [b]^2_4 = [3]_4 [c]^2_4
&\\Leftrightarrow [a]^2_4 + [b]^2_4 = [-1]_4 ([c]^2_4) \\\\
&\\Leftrightarrow [a]^2_4 + [b]^2_4 + [c]^2_4 = [0]_4 \\\\
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since 0 is even, this condition gives us that either two of the numbers have to be odd, or none of them are. However, looking back at the first equation, if {\i c} is even, then [{\i c}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?0, and [3]{\sub 4}[{\i c}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?0, which means that {\i a} and {\i b} must be both even or both odd. If {\i a} and {\i b} are both odd (i.e., either congruent to 1 or \u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1), then [{\i a}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?1 and [{\i b}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?1 and their sum, supposedly equal to 0, is congruent to 2, which is a contradiction. In this case, both {\i a} and {\i b} must be even.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now if {\i c} is odd, then [3]{\sub 4}[{\i c}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?[3]{\sub 4}[1]{\sub 4}\u8196?=\u8196?[3]{\sub 4}\u8196?=\u8196?[\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1]{\sub 4}. Since {\i c} is odd, only one of {\i a} or {\i b} must be odd. Without loss of generality, we choose that to be {\i b}, in which case [{\i b}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?1. Our "the three sum to 0" equation above then tells us that [{\i a}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?[2]{\sub 4}\u8196?=\u8196?[0]{\sub 4}, so [{\i a}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?[2]{\sub 4}, which is a contradiction, because there is no number [{\i a}]{\sub 4} such that [{\i a}]{\sub 4}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?[2]{\sub 4} (the image of the squaring function is \{[0]{\sub 4},\u8198?[1]{\sub 4}\}). Therefore, {\i c} cannot be odd.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We\u8217've thus shown that the only case not leading to a contradition is the case where all three numbers are even, and this applies to the original equation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Letting {\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i k}, {\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i l}, {\i c}\u8196?=\u8196?2{\i m}, you would have {\i k}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i l}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i m}{\super 2}, which is just a rewriting of our initial equation. After iteration this process until a maximal instance of 2\u8217's has been removed from the prime factorization of each number, we will eventually reach a point where either {\i k}, {\i l}, or (non-exclusive) {\i m} is odd, which is a contradiction. Therefore, there are no integers {\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c} such that {\i a}{\super 2}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\super 2}\u8196?=\u8196?3{\i c}{\super 2}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This exercise is interesting because it teaches us that number theoretic equations that rely on odd and evenness can effectively be studied using \u8484?/4\u8484?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.13)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that if gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1, then there exist integers {\i a} and {\i b} such that {\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1. (Use Corollary 2.5.) Conversely, prove that if {\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1 for some integers {\i a} and {\i b}, then gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is known as B\u233?zout\u8217's identity. We remind Corollary 2.5.: The class [{\i m}]{\sub {\i n}} generates \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? if and only if gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1. So this exercise can also be reduced to proving that \u8707?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1 if and only if [{\i m}]{\sub {\i n}} generates \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?\u8707?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We suppose that gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1, by Corollary 2.5, we have that [{\i m}]{\sub {\i n}} generates \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484?. This means that for every [{\i c}]{\sub {\i n}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?/{\i n}\u8484?, there exists {\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484? such that [{\i a}{\i m}]{\sub {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?[{\i c}]{\sub {\i n}}. If we take [{\i c}]{\sub {\i n}}\u8196?=\u8196?[1]{\sub {\i n}}, this means that {\i a}{\i m}\u8196?=\u8196?1\u8197?+\u8197?{\i k}{\i n} for some {\i k}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. We can rewrite this as {\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1 for {\i b}\u8196?=\u8196?\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i k}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b \u8707?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We suppose that \u8707?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}{\i m}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}\u8196?=\u8196?1. We can write this as {\i a}{\i m}\u8196?=\u8196?1\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}, which means that {\i m} divides 1\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}{\i n}. Suppose {\i m} and {\i n} have a common prime factor {\i p}: this prime factor would divide {\i m} and {\i n}, and thus would divide 1\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}{\i n} (equivalently its opposite {\i b}{\i n}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?1) and {\i b}{\i n}. However, this is a contradiction, because the only number that can divide two numbers that are off by 1 is 1. Therefore, {\i m} and {\i n} have no common prime factors, and gcd\u8198?({\i m},\u8198?{\i n})\u8196?=\u8196?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.14)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 State and prove an analog of Lemma 2.2, showing that the multiplication on \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? is a well-defined operation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We remind Lemma 2.2: If {\i a}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i a}\u8242?mod{\i n} and{\i b}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i b}\u8242?mod{\i n}, then ({\i a}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b})\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?({\i a}\u8242?\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b}\u8242?)mod{\i n}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Our analogue is thus: {\i a}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i a}\u8242?mod{\i n} and{\i b}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i b}\u8242?mod{\i n}, then ({\i a}\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i b})\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?({\i a}\u8242?\u8197?\u215?\u8197?{\i b}\u8242?)mod{\i n}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now show that it is well-defined (there exists a commutative square diagram with an epimorphism from \u8484? to \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? in one direction, and with the respective multiplications in the other). We take {\i a}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i a}\u8242?mod{\i n} and{\i b}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i b}\u8242?mod{\i n}. This means that {\i a}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i k}{\i n} and {\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i l}{\i n} for some {\i k},\u8198?{\i l}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?. We have that {\i a}{\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8242?{\i b}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}{\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}{\i b}\u8242?\u8197?+\u8197?{\i a}{\i b}\u8242?\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8242?{\i b}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}({\i b}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i b}\u8242?)\u8197?+\u8197?({\i a}\u8197?\u8722?\u8197?{\i a}\u8242?){\i b}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}({\i l}{\i n})\u8197?+\u8197?({\i k}{\i n}){\i b}\u8242?\u8196?=\u8196?{\i n}({\i a}{\i l}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i k}{\i b}\u8242?). The first and last terms of this equation give us that {\i a}{\i b}\u8196?\u8801?\u8196?{\i a}\u8242?{\i b}\u8242?mod{\i n}, as needed.\par}
