{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For {\i d}\u8196?\u8804?\u8196?{\i n}, define an injective function \u8484?/{\i d}\u8484?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i n}} preserving the operation: that is, such that the sum of equivalence classes in \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? corresponds to the product of the corresponding permutations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can define the function {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?\u8484?/{\i d}\u8484?\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i S}{\sub {\i n}} as {\i f}([{\i a}]{\sub {\i d}})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i a}}, where {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i a}} is the permutation that maps {\i i} to {\i i}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i a} modulo {\i d} (our Caesar cypher mentioned above, over the {\i d} first elements, or any choice of {\i d} elements really).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This function is injective because the permutation {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i a}} is uniquely determined by {\i a}. This can immediately be seen by studying with which element the first element (which we can label 0) is replaced: it is replaced with {\i a} (the {\i a}-th element), leading to {\i d} distinct outputs for {\i d} possible inputs. More formally, if {\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?\u8484?/{\i d}\u8484?,\u8198?{\i a}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i b}, then {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i a}} and {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i b}} are distinct permutations, as they map {\i i} to {\i i}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i a} and {\i i}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b} respectively, and {\i a}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i b} implies that {\i i}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i a}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i i}\u8197?+\u8197?{\i b} for any {\i i}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can see that the sum of equivalence classes in \u8484?/{\i n}\u8484? corresponds to the product of the corresponding permutations through the following commutative diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{tikzcd\}
    \\begin\{array\}\{c\} (\\mathbb\{Z\}/d\\mathbb\{Z\})^2 \\\\ ([a]_d, [b]_d) \\end\{array\} & \\begin\{array\}\{c\} \\mathbb\{Z\}/d\\mathbb\{Z\} \\\\ \{[a+b]_d\} \\end\{array\} \\\\
    \\begin\{array\}\{c\} S_n^2 \\\\ (\\sigma_a,\\sigma_b) \\end\{array\} & \\begin\{array\}\{c\} S_n \\\\ \\sigma_\{a+b\} \\end\{array\}
    \\arrow["\{+_\{\\mathbb\{Z\}/d\\mathbb\{Z\}\}\}", from=1-1, to=1-2]
    \\arrow["\{(f,f)\}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \\arrow["f", from=1-2, to=2-2]
    \\arrow["\{\\circ_\{S_n\}\}"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
\\end\{tikzcd\}$$\par}
